# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: requests-http
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:requests-http/authentication] This document discusses using various kinds of authentication with Requests.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Many web services require authentication, and there are many different types.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Below, we outline various forms of authentication available in Requests, from the simple to the complex.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Many web services that require authentication accept HTTP Basic Auth.
[src:requests-http/authentication] This is the simplest kind, and Requests supports it straight out of the box.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Providing the credentials in a tuple like this is exactly the same as the `HTTPBasicAuth` example above.
[src:requests-http/authentication] If no authentication method is given with the `auth` argument, Requests will attempt to get the authentication credentials for the URL’s hostname from the user’s netrc file.
[src:requests-http/authentication] The netrc file overrides raw HTTP authentication headers set with *headers=*.
[src:requests-http/authentication] If credentials for the hostname are found, the request is sent with HTTP Basic Auth.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Requests will search for the netrc file at *~/.netrc*, *~/_netrc*, or at the path specified by the *NETRC* environment variable.
[src:requests-http/authentication] *~* denotes the user’s home directory, which is *$HOME* on Unix based systems and *%USERPROFILE%* on Windows.
[src:requests-http/authentication] A common form of authentication for several web APIs is OAuth.
[src:requests-http/authentication] For more information on how to OAuth flow works, please see the official OAuth website.
[src:requests-http/authentication] The `requests-oauthlib` library also handles OAuth 2, the authentication mechanism underpinning OpenID Connect.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Requests is designed to allow other forms of authentication to be easily and quickly plugged in.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Members of the open-source community frequently write authentication handlers for more complicated or less commonly-used forms of authentication.
[src:requests-http/authentication] If you want to use any of these forms of authentication, go straight to their GitHub page and follow the instructions.
[src:requests-http/authentication] If you can’t find a good implementation of the form of authentication you want, you can implement it yourself.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Requests makes it easy to add your own forms of authentication.
[src:requests-http/authentication] When an authentication handler is attached to a request, it is called during request setup.
[src:requests-http/authentication] The `__call__` method must therefore do whatever is required to make the authentication work.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Some forms of authentication will additionally add hooks to provide further functionality.
[src:requests-http/authentication] Further examples can be found under the Requests organization and in the `auth.py` file.
[src:requests-http/http-client] On the Web, a **user agent** is a software agent responsible for retrieving and facilitating end-user interaction with Web content.
[src:requests-http/http-client] This includes all web browsers, such as Google Chrome and Safari, some email clients, standalone download managers like youtube-dl, and other command-line utilities like cURL.
[src:requests-http/http-client] The user agent is the client in a client–server system.
[src:requests-http/http-client] The HTTP User-Agent header is intended to clearly identify the agent to the server.
[src:requests-http/http-client] However, this header can be omitted or spoofed, so some websites use other detection methods.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] An **HTTP cookie** (also called **web cookie**, **Internet cookie**, **browser cookie**, or simply **cookie**) is a small block of data created by a web server while a user is browsing a website and placed on the user's computer or other device by the user's web browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are placed on the device used to access a website, and more than one cookie may be placed on a user's device during a session.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies serve useful and sometimes essential functions on the web.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] They enable web servers to store stateful information (such as items added in the shopping cart in an online store) on the user's device or to track the user's browsing activity (including clicking particular buttons, logging in, or recording which pages were visited in the past).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] They can also be used to save information that the user previously entered into form fields, such as names, addresses, passwords, and payment card numbers for subsequent use.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie* was coined by web-browser programmer Lou Montulli.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] It was derived from the term *magic cookie*, which is a packet of data a program receives and sends back unchanged, used by Unix programmers.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Magic cookies were already used in computing when computer programmer Lou Montulli had the idea of using them in web communications in June 1994.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] At the time, he was an employee of Netscape Communications, which was developing an e-commerce application for MCI.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Vint Cerf and John Klensin represented MCI in technical discussions with Netscape Communications.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] MCI did not want its servers to have to retain partial transaction states, which led them to ask Netscape to find a way to store that state in each user's computer instead.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies provided a solution to the problem of reliably implementing a virtual shopping cart.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Together with John Giannandrea, Montulli wrote the initial Netscape cookie specification the same year.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Version 0.9beta of Mosaic Netscape, released on 13 October 1994, supported cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The first use of cookies (out of the labs) was checking whether visitors to the Netscape website had already visited the site.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Montulli applied for a patent for the cookie technology in 1995, which was granted in 1998.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Support for cookies was integrated with Internet Explorer in version 2, released in October 1995.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The introduction of cookies was not widely known to the public at the time.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In particular, cookies were accepted by default, and users were not notified of their presence.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The public learned about cookies after the *Financial Times* published an article about them on 12 February 1996.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In the same year, cookies received a lot of media attention, especially because of potential privacy implications.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Federal Trade Commission hearings in 1996 and 1997.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The development of the formal cookie specifications was already ongoing.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In particular, the first discussions about a formal specification started in April 1995 on the www-talk mailing list.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A special working group within the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) was formed.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Two alternative proposals for introducing state in HTTP transactions had been proposed by Brian Behlendorf and David Kristol respectively.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] But the group, headed by Kristol himself and Lou Montulli, soon decided to use the Netscape specification as a starting point.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In February 1996, the working group identified third-party cookies as a considerable privacy threat.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The specification produced by the group was eventually published as RFC 2109 in February 1997.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] It specifies that third-party cookies were either not allowed at all, or at least not enabled by default.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] At this time, advertising companies were already using third-party cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The recommendation about third-party cookies of RFC 2109 was not followed by Netscape and Internet Explorer.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2109 was superseded by RFC 2965 in October 2000.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] RFC 2965 added a `Set-Cookie2` header field, which informally came to be called "RFC 2965-style cookies" as opposed to the original `Set-Cookie` header field which was called "Netscape-style cookies".
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] `Set-Cookie2` was seldom used, however, and was deprecated in RFC 6265 in April 2011 which was written as a definitive specification for cookies as used in the real world.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] No modern browser recognizes the `Set-Cookie2` header field.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A *session cookie* (also known as an *in-memory cookie*, *transient cookie* or *non-persistent cookie*) exists only in temporary memory while the user navigates a website.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies expire or are deleted when the user closes the web browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are identified by the browser by the absence of an expiration date assigned to them.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A *persistent cookie* expires at a specific date or after a specific length of time.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For the persistent cookie's lifespan set by its creator, its information will be transmitted to the server every time the user visits the website that it belongs to, or every time the user views a resource belonging to that website from another website (such as an advertisement).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, persistent cookies are sometimes referred to as *tracking cookies* because they can be used by advertisers to record information about a user's web browsing habits over an extended period of time.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Persistent cookies are also used for reasons such as keeping users logged into their accounts on websites, to avoid re-entering login credentials at every visit.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A *secure cookie* can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection (i.e.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] They cannot be transmitted over unencrypted connections (i.e.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This makes the cookie less likely to be exposed to cookie theft via eavesdropping.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is made secure by adding the `Secure` flag to the cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] An *http-only cookie* cannot be accessed by client-side APIs, such as JavaScript.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This restriction eliminates the threat of cookie theft via cross-site scripting (XSS).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, the cookie remains vulnerable to cross-site tracing (XST) and cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A cookie is given this characteristic by adding the `HttpOnly` flag to the cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In 2016 Google Chrome version 51 introduced a new kind of cookie with attribute `SameSite` with possible values of `Strict`, `Lax` or `None`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] With attribute `SameSite=Strict`, the browsers would only send cookies to a target domain that is the same as the origin domain.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This would effectively mitigate cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] With `SameSite=Lax`, browsers would send cookies with requests to a target domain even it is different from the origin domain, but only for *safe* requests such as GET (POST is unsafe) and not third-party cookies (inside iframe).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Attribute `SameSite=None` would allow third-party (cross-site) cookies, however, most browsers require secure attribute on SameSite=None cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The Same-site cookie is incorporated into a new RFC draft for "Cookies: HTTP State Management Mechanism" to update RFC 6265 (if approved).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Chrome, Firefox, and Edge started to support Same-site cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The key of rollout is the treatment of existing cookies without the SameSite attribute defined, Chrome has been treating those existing cookies as if SameSite=None, this would let all website/applications run as before.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Google intended to change that default to `SameSite=Lax` in Chrome 80 planned to be released in February 2020, but due to potential for breakage of those applications/websites that rely on third-party/cross-site cookies and COVID-19 circumstances, Google postponed this change to Chrome 84.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A *supercookie* is a cookie with an origin of a top-level domain (such as `.com`) or a public suffix (such as `.co.uk`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Ordinary cookies, by contrast, have an origin of a specific domain name, such as `example.com`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Supercookies can be a potential security concern and are therefore often blocked by web browsers.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If unblocked by the browser, an attacker in control of a malicious website could set a supercookie and potentially disrupt or impersonate legitimate user requests to another website that shares the same top-level domain or public suffix as the malicious website.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, a supercookie with an origin of `.com` could maliciously affect a request made to `example.com`, even if the cookie did not originate from `example.com`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This can be used to fake logins or change user information.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List helps to mitigate the risk that supercookies pose.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The Public Suffix List is a cross-vendor initiative that aims to provide an accurate and up-to-date list of domain name suffixes.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Older versions of browsers may not have an up-to-date list, and will therefore be vulnerable to supercookies from certain domains.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The term *supercookie* is also used for tracking technologies that do not rely on HTTP cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Two such *supercookie* mechanisms were found on Microsoft websites in August 2011: cookie syncing that respawned MUID (machine unique identifier) cookies, and ETag cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Due to media attention, Microsoft later disabled this code.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In a 2021 blog post, Mozilla used the term *supercookie* to refer to the use of browser cache as a means of tracking users across sites.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Zero or more attributes (name/value pairs).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Attributes store information such as the cookie's expiration, domain, and flags (such as `Secure` and `HttpOnly`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies were originally introduced to provide a way for users to record items they want to purchase as they navigate throughout a website (a virtual *shopping cart* or *shopping basket*).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Today, however, the contents of a user's shopping cart are usually stored in a database on the server, rather than in a cookie on the client.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] To keep track of which user is assigned to which shopping cart, the server sends a cookie to the client that contains a unique session identifier (typically, a long string of random letters and numbers).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Because cookies are sent to the server with every request the client makes, that session identifier will be sent back to the server every time the user visits a new page on the website, which lets the server know which shopping cart to display to the user.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Another popular use of cookies is for logging into websites.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] When the user visits a website's login page, the web server typically sends the client a cookie containing a unique session identifier.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] When the user successfully logs in, the server remembers that that particular session identifier has been authenticated and grants the user access to its services.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Because session cookies only contain a unique session identifier, this makes the amount of personal information that a website can save about each user virtually limitless—the website is not limited to restrictions concerning how large a cookie can be.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies also help to improve page load times, since the amount of information in a session cookie is small and requires little bandwidth.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can be used to remember information about the user in order to show relevant content to that user over time.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, a web server might send a cookie containing the username that was last used to log into a website, so that it may be filled in automatically the next time the user logs in.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Many websites use cookies for personalization based on the user's preferences.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Users select their preferences by entering them in a web form and submitting the form to the server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The server encodes the preferences in a cookie and sends the cookie back to the browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This way, every time the user accesses a page on the website, the server can personalize the page according to the user's preferences.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, the Google search engine once used cookies to allow users (even non-registered ones) to decide how many search results per page they wanted to see.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Also, DuckDuckGo uses cookies to allow users to set the viewing preferences like colors of the web page.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Tracking cookies are used to track users' web browsing habits.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This can also be done to some extent by using the IP address of the computer requesting the page or the referer field of the HTTP request header, but cookies allow for greater precision.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] From this point on, the cookie will automatically be sent by the browser to the server every time a new page from the site is requested.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The server not only sends the page as usual but also stores the URL of the requested page, the date/time of the request, and the cookie in a log file.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] By analyzing this log file, it is then possible to discover which pages the user has visited, in what sequence, and for how long.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Corporations exploit users' web habits by tracking cookies to collect information about buying habits.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The *Wall Street Journal* found that America's top fifty websites installed an average of sixty-four pieces of tracking technology onto computers, resulting in a total of 3,180 tracking files.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The data can then be collected and sold to bidding corporations.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are arbitrary pieces of data, usually chosen and first sent by the web server, and stored on the client computer by the web browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The browser then sends them back to the server with every request, introducing states (memory of previous events) into otherwise stateless HTTP transactions.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Without cookies, each retrieval of a web page or component of a web page would be an isolated event, largely unrelated to all other page views made by the user on the website.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Although cookies are usually set by the web server, they can also be set by the client using a scripting language such as JavaScript (unless the cookie's `HttpOnly` flag is set, in which case the cookie cannot be modified by scripting languages).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies are set using the `Set-Cookie` header field, sent in an HTTP response from the web server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This header field instructs the web browser to store the cookie and send it back in future requests to the server (the browser will ignore this header field if it does not support cookies or has disabled cookies).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The server's HTTP response contains the contents of the website's homepage.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] But it also instructs the browser to set two cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The first, *theme*, is considered to be a *session cookie* since it does not have an `Expires` or `Max-Age` attribute.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Session cookies are intended to be deleted by the browser when the browser closes.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The second, *sessionToken*, is considered to be a *persistent cookie* since it contains an `Expires` attribute, which instructs the browser to delete the cookie at a specific date and time.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Next, the browser sends another request to visit the `spec.html` page on the website.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This way, the server knows that this HTTP request is related to the previous one.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The server would answer by sending the requested page, possibly including more `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response in order to instruct the browser to add new cookies, modify existing cookies, or remove existing cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] To remove a cookie, the server must include a `Set-Cookie` header field with an expiration date in the past.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The value of a cookie may consist of any printable ASCII character (`!` through `~`, Unicode `\u0021` through `\u007E`) excluding `,`and`;` and whitespace characters.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The name of a cookie excludes the same characters, as well as `=`, since that is the delimiter between the name and value.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The cookie standard RFC 2965 is more restrictive but not implemented by browsers.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The term *cookie crumb* is sometimes used to refer to a cookie's name–value pair.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be set by scripting languages such as JavaScript that run within the browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In JavaScript, the object `document.cookie` is used for this purpose.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, the instruction `document.cookie = "temperature=20"` creates a cookie of name *temperature* and value *20*.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In addition to a name and value, cookies can also have one or more attributes.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Browsers do not include cookie attributes in requests to the server—they only send the cookie's name and value.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookie attributes are used by browsers to determine when to delete a cookie, block a cookie or whether to send a cookie to the server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The `Domain` and `Path` attributes define the scope of the cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] They essentially tell the browser what website the cookie belongs to.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For security reasons, cookies can only be set on the current resource's top domain and its subdomains, and not for another domain and its subdomains.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, the website `example.org` cannot set a cookie that has a domain of `foo.com` because this would allow the website `example.org` to control the cookies of the domain `foo.com`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If a cookie's `Domain` and `Path` attributes are not specified by the server, they default to the domain and path of the resource that was requested.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, in most browsers there is a difference between a cookie set from `foo.com` without a domain, and a cookie set with the `foo.com` domain.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In the former case, the cookie will only be sent for requests to `foo.com`, also known as a host-only cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In the latter case, all subdomains are also included (for example, `docs.foo.com`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A notable exception to this general rule is Edge prior to Windows 10 RS3 and Internet Explorer prior to IE 11 and Windows 10 RS4 (April 2018), which always sends cookies to subdomains regardless of whether the cookie was set with or without a domain.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Below is an example of some `Set-Cookie` header fields in the HTTP response of a website after a user logged in.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `LSID`, has no `Domain` attribute, and has a `Path` attribute set to `/accounts`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This tells the browser to use the cookie only when requesting pages contained in `docs.foo.com/accounts` (the domain is derived from the request domain).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The other two cookies, `HSID` and `SSID`, would be used when the browser requests any subdomain in `.foo.com` on any path (for example `www.foo.com/bar`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The prepending dot is optional in recent standards, but can be added for compatibility with RFC 2109 based implementations.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The `Expires` attribute defines a specific date and time for when the browser should delete the cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The date and time are specified in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YYYY HH:MM:SS GMT`, or in the form `Wdy, DD Mon YY HH:MM:SS GMT` for values of YY where YY is greater than or equal to 0 and less than or equal to 69.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Alternatively, the `Max-Age` attribute can be used to set the cookie's expiration as an interval of seconds in the future, relative to the time the browser received the cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The first cookie, `lu`, is set to expire sometime on 15 January 2013.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] It will be used by the client browser until that time.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The second cookie, `made_write_conn`, does not have an expiration date, making it a session cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] It will be deleted after the user closes their browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The third cookie, `reg_fb_gate`, has its value changed to *deleted*, with an expiration time in the past.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The browser will delete this cookie right away because its expiration time is in the past.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Note that cookie will only be deleted if the domain and path attributes in the `Set-Cookie` field match the values used when the cookie was created.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] As of 2016 Internet Explorer did not support `Max-Age`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes do not have associated values.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Rather, the presence of just their attribute names indicates that their behaviors should be enabled.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The `Secure` attribute is meant to keep cookie communication limited to encrypted transmission, directing browsers to use cookies only via secure/encrypted connections.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, if a web server sets a cookie with a secure attribute from a non-secure connection, the cookie can still be intercepted when it is sent to the user by man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Therefore, for maximum security, cookies with the Secure attribute should only be set over a secure connection.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The `HttpOnly` attribute directs browsers not to expose cookies through channels other than HTTP (and HTTPS) requests.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This means that the cookie cannot be accessed via client-side scripting languages (notably JavaScript), and therefore cannot be stolen easily via cross-site scripting (a pervasive attack technique).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Most modern browsers support cookies and allow the user to disable them.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Add-on tools for managing cookie permissions also exist.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies have some important implications for the privacy and anonymity of web users.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] While cookies are sent only to the server setting them or a server in the same Internet domain, a web page may contain images or other components stored on servers in other domains.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies that are set during retrieval of these components are called *third-party cookies*.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A third-party cookie, belongs to a domain different from the one shown in the address bar.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This sort of cookie typically appears when web pages feature content from external websites, such as banner advertisements.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This opens up the potential for tracking the user's browsing history and is used by advertisers to serve relevant advertisements to each user.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] As an example, suppose a user visits `www.example.org`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This website contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com`, which, when downloaded, sets a cookie belonging to the advertisement's domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Then, the user visits another website, `www.foo.com`, which also contains an advertisement from `ad.foxytracking.com` and sets a cookie belonging to that domain (`ad.foxytracking.com`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Eventually, both of these cookies will be sent to the advertiser when loading their advertisements or visiting their website.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The advertiser can then use these cookies to build up a browsing history of the user across all the websites that have ads from this advertiser, through the use of the HTTP referer header field.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] As of 2014, some websites were setting cookies readable for over 100 third-party domains.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] On average, a single website was setting 10 cookies, with a maximum number of cookies (first- and third-party) reaching over 800.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The older standards for cookies, RFC 2109 and RFC 2965, recommend that browsers should protect user privacy and not allow sharing of cookies between servers by default.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, the newer standard, RFC 6265, explicitly allows user agents to implement whichever third-party cookie policy they wish.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Most modern web browsers contain privacy settings that can block third-party cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Since 2020, Apple Safari, Firefox, and Brave block all third-party cookies by default.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Safari allows embedded sites to use Storage Access API to request permission to set first-party cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In May 2020, Google Chrome 83 introduced new features to block third-party cookies by default in its Incognito mode for private browsing, making blocking optional during normal browsing.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The same update also added an option to block first-party cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In April 2024, Chrome postponed third-party cookie blocking by default to 2025.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In July 2024, Google announced plan to avoid blocking third-party cookies by default and instead prompt users to allow third-party cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The possibility of building a profile of users is a privacy threat, especially when tracking is done across multiple domains using third-party cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For this reason, some countries have legislation about cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Website operators who do not disclose third-party cookie use to consumers run the risk of harming consumer trust if cookie use is discovered.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Having clear disclosure (such as in a privacy policy) tends to eliminate any negative effects of such cookie discovery.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The government of the United States set strict rules on setting cookies in 2000 after it was disclosed that the White House drug policy office used cookies to track computer users viewing its online anti-drug advertising.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, privacy activist Daniel Brandt found that the CIA had been leaving persistent cookies on computers that had visited its website.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] When notified it was violating policy, CIA stated that these cookies were not intentionally set and stopped setting them.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] On 25 December 2005, Brandt discovered that the National Security Agency (NSA) had been leaving two persistent cookies on visitors' computers due to a software upgrade.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] After being informed, the NSA immediately disabled the cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In 2002, the European Union launched the Directive on Privacy and Electronic Communications (e-Privacy Directive), a policy requiring end users' consent for the placement of cookies, and similar technologies for storing and accessing information on users' equipment.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In particular, Article 5 Paragraph 3 mandates that storing technically unnecessary data on a user's computer can only be done if the user is provided information about how this data is used, and the user is given the possibility of denying this storage operation.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The Directive does not require users to authorise or be provided notice of cookie usage that are functionally required for delivering a service they have requested, for example to retain settings, store log-in sessions, or remember what is in a user's shopping basket.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In 2009, the law was amended by Directive 2009/136/EC, which included a change to Article 5, Paragraph 3.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Instead of having an option for users to opt out of cookie storage, the revised Directive requires consent to be obtained for cookie storage.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The definition of consent is cross-referenced to the definition in European data protection law, firstly the Data Protection Directive 1995 and subsequently the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] As the definition of consent was strengthened in the text of the GDPR, this increased the quality of consent required by those storing and accessing information such as cookies on users devices.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In a case decided under the Data Protection Directive however, the Court of Justice of the European Union later confirmed however that the previous law implied the same strong quality of consent as the current instrument.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In addition to the requirement of consent which stems from storing or accessing information on a user's terminal device, the information in many cookies will be considered personal data under the GDPR alone, and will require a legal basis to process.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This has been the case since the 1995 Data Protection Directive, which used an identical definition of personal data, although the GDPR in interpretative Recital 30 clarifies that cookie identifiers are included.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] While not all data processing under the GDPR requires consent, the characteristics of behavioural advertising mean that it is difficult or impossible to justify under any other ground.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Consent under the combination of the GDPR and e-Privacy Directive has to meet a number of conditions in relation to cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] It must be freely given and unambiguous: preticked boxes were banned under both the Data Protection Directive 1995 and the GDPR (Recital 32).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The GDPR is specific that consent must be as 'easy to withdraw as to give', meaning that a reject-all button must be as easy to access in terms of clicks and visibility as an 'accept all' button.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] It must be specific and informed, meaning that consent relates to particular purposes for the use of this data, and all organisations seeking to use this consent must be specifically named.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The Court of Justice of the European Union has also ruled that consent must be 'efficient and timely', meaning that it must be gained before cookies are laid and data processing begins instead of afterwards.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The industry's response has been largely negative.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Robert Bond of the law firm Speechly Bircham describes the effects as "far-reaching and incredibly onerous" for "all UK companies".
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Simon Davis of Privacy International argues that proper enforcement would "destroy the entire industry".
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, scholars note that the onerous nature of cookie pop-ups stems from an attempt to continue to operate a business model through convoluted requests that may be incompatible with the GDPR.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Academic studies and regulators both describe widespread non-compliance with the law.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A study scraping 10,000 UK websites found that only 11.8% of sites adhered to minimal legal requirements, with only 33.4% of websites studied providing a mechanism to reject cookies that was as easy to use as accepting them.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A study of 17,000 websites found that 84% of sites breached this criterion, finding additionally that many laid third party cookies with no notice at all.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A W3C specification called P3P was proposed for servers to communicate their privacy policy to browsers, allowing automatic, user-configurable handling.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, few websites implement the specification, and the W3C has discontinued work on the specification.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Third-party cookies can be blocked by most browsers to increase privacy and reduce tracking by advertising and tracking companies without negatively affecting the user's web experience on all sites.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Some sites operate 'cookie walls', which make access to a site conditional on allowing cookies either technically in a browser, through pressing 'accept', or both.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In 2020, the European Data Protection Board, composed of all EU data protection regulators, stated that cookie walls were illegal.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Many advertising operators have an opt-out option to behavioural advertising, with a generic cookie in the browser stopping behavioural advertising.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, this is often ineffective against many forms of tracking, such as first-party tracking that is growing in popularity to avoid the impact of browsers blocking third party cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Furthermore, if such a setting is more difficult to place than the acceptance of tracking, it remains in breach of the conditions of the e-Privacy Directive.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Most websites use cookies as the only identifiers for user sessions, because other methods of identifying web users have limitations and vulnerabilities.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If a website uses cookies as session identifiers, attackers can impersonate users' requests by stealing a full set of victims' cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] From the web server's point of view, a request from an attacker then has the same authentication as the victim's requests; thus the request is performed on behalf of the victim's session.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Listed here are various scenarios of cookie theft and user session hijacking (even without stealing user cookies) that work with websites relying solely on HTTP cookies for user identification.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Traffic on a network can be intercepted and read by computers on the network other than the sender and receiver (particularly over unencrypted open Wi-Fi).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This traffic includes cookies sent on ordinary unencrypted HTTP sessions.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Where network traffic is not encrypted, attackers can therefore read the communications of other users on the network, including HTTP cookies as well as the entire contents of the conversations, for the purpose of a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] An attacker could use intercepted cookies to impersonate a user and perform a malicious task, such as transferring money out of the victim's bank account.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This issue can be resolved by securing the communication between the user's computer and the server by employing Transport Layer Security (HTTPS protocol) to encrypt the connection.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] A server can specify the `Secure` flag while setting a cookie, which will cause the browser to send the cookie only over an encrypted channel, such as a TLS connection.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to cause a DNS server to cache a fabricated DNS entry (called DNS cache poisoning), then this could allow the attacker to gain access to a user's cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, an attacker could use DNS cache poisoning to create a fabricated DNS entry of `f12345.www.example.com` that points to the IP address of the attacker's server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The attacker can then post an image URL from his own server (for example, `http://f12345.www.example.com/img_4_cookie.jpg`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Victims reading the attacker's message would download this image from `f12345.www.example.com`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Since `f12345.www.example.com` is a sub-domain of `www.example.com`, victims' browsers would submit all `example.com`-related cookies to the attacker's server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If an attacker is able to accomplish this, it is usually the fault of the Internet service providers for not properly securing their DNS servers.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] However, the severity of this attack can be lessened if the target website uses secure cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the attacker would have the extra challenge of obtaining the target website's TLS certificate from a certificate authority, since secure cookies can only be transmitted over an encrypted connection.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Without a matching TLS certificate, victims' browsers would display a warning message about the attacker's invalid certificate, which would help deter users from visiting the attacker's fraudulent website and sending the attacker their cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Cookies can also be stolen using a technique called cross-site scripting.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This occurs when an attacker takes advantage of a website that allows its users to post unfiltered HTML and JavaScript content.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] By posting malicious HTML and JavaScript code, the attacker can cause the victim's web browser to send the victim's cookies to a website the attacker controls.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] When another user clicks on this link, the browser executes the piece of code within the `onclick` attribute, thus replacing the string `document.cookie` with the list of cookies that are accessible from the current page.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] As a result, this list of cookies is sent to the `attacker.com` server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If the attacker's malicious posting is on an HTTPS website `https://www.example.com`, secure cookies will also be sent to attacker.com in plain text.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] It is the responsibility of the website developers to filter out such malicious code.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Such attacks can be mitigated by using HttpOnly cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] These cookies will not be accessible by client-side scripting languages like JavaScript, and therefore, the attacker will not be able to gather these cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In older versions of many browsers, there were security holes in the implementation of the XMLHttpRequest API.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This API allows pages to specify a proxy server that would get the reply, and this proxy server is not subject to the same-origin policy.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, a victim is reading an attacker's posting on `www.example.com`, and the attacker's script is executed in the victim's browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] The script generates a request to `www.example.com` with the proxy server `attacker.com`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Since the request is for `www.example.com`, all `example.com` cookies will be sent along with the request, but routed through the attacker's proxy server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Hence, the attacker would be able to harvest the victim's cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] This attack would not work with secure cookies, since they can only be transmitted over HTTPS connections, and the HTTPS protocol dictates end-to-end encryption (i.e. the information is encrypted on the user's browser and decrypted on the destination server).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In this case, the proxy server would only see the raw, encrypted bytes of the HTTP request.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] For example, Bob might be browsing a chat forum where another user, Mallory, has posted a message.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If Bob's bank keeps his authentication information in a cookie, and if the cookie hasn't expired, then the attempt by Bob's browser to load the image will submit the withdrawal form with his cookie, thus authorizing a transaction without Bob's approval.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Besides privacy concerns, cookies also have some technical drawbacks.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] In particular, they do not always accurately identify users, they can be used for security attacks, and they are often at odds with the Representational State Transfer (REST) software architectural style.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] If more than one browser is used on a computer, each usually has a separate storage area for cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Hence, cookies do not identify a person, but a combination of a user account, a computer, and a web browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Thus, anyone who uses multiple accounts, computers, or browsers has multiple sets of cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p01] Likewise, cookies do not differentiate between multiple users who share the same user account, computer, and browser.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Some of the operations that can be done using cookies can also be done using other mechanisms.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] A JSON Web Token (JWT) is a self-contained packet of information that can be used to store user identity and authenticity information.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This allows them to be used in place of session cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Unlike cookies, which are automatically attached to each HTTP request by the browser, JWTs must be explicitly attached to each HTTP request by the web application.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The HTTP protocol includes the basic access authentication and the digest access authentication protocols, which allow access to a web page only when the user has provided the correct username and password.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] If the server requires such credentials for granting access to a web page, the browser requests them from the user and, once obtained, the browser stores and sends them in every subsequent page request.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This information can be used to track the user.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The query string part of the URL is the part that is typically used for this purpose, but other parts can be used as well.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The Java Servlet and PHP session mechanisms both use this method if cookies are not enabled.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This method consists of the web server appending query strings containing a unique session identifier to all the links inside of a web page.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] When the user follows a link, the browser sends the query string to the server, allowing the server to identify the user and maintain state.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] These kinds of query strings are very similar to cookies in that both contain arbitrary pieces of information chosen by the server and both are sent back to the server on every request.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Since a query string is part of a URL, if that URL is later reused, the same attached piece of information will be sent to the server, which could lead to confusion.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] For example, if the preferences of a user are encoded in the query string of a URL and the user sends this URL to another user by e-mail, those preferences will be used for that other user as well.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Moreover, if the same user accesses the same page multiple times from different sources, there is no guarantee that the same query string will be used each time.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] For example, if a user visits a page by coming from a page *internal to the site* the first time, and then visits the same page by coming from an *external search engine* the second time, the query strings would likely be different.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] If cookies were used in this situation, the cookies would be the same.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Other drawbacks of query strings are related to security.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Storing data that identifies a session in a query string enables session fixation attacks, referer logging attacks and other security exploits.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Transferring session identifiers as HTTP cookies is more secure.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Another form of session tracking is to use web forms with hidden fields.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This technique is very similar to using URL query strings to hold the information and has many of the same advantages and drawbacks.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] In fact, if the form is handled with the HTTP GET method, then this technique is similar to using URL query strings, since the GET method adds the form fields to the URL as a query string.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] But most forms are handled with HTTP POST, which causes the form information, including the hidden fields, to be sent in the HTTP request body, which is neither part of the URL, nor of a cookie.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This approach presents two advantages from the point of view of the tracker.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] First, having the tracking information placed in the HTTP request body rather than in the URL means it will not be noticed by the average user.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Second, the session information is not copied when the user copies the URL (to bookmark the page or send it via email, for example).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] All current web browsers can store a fairly large amount of data (2–32 MB) via JavaScript using the DOM property `window.name`.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This data can be used instead of session cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The technique can be coupled with JSON/JavaScript objects to store complex sets of session variables on the client side.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The downside is that every separate window or tab will initially have an empty `window.name` property when opened.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] In some respects, this can be more secure than cookies because its contents are not automatically sent to the server on every request like cookies are, so it is not vulnerable to network cookie sniffing attacks.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Some users may be tracked based on the IP address of the computer requesting the page.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The server knows the IP address of the computer running the browser (or the proxy, if any is used) and could theoretically link a user's session to this IP address.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] However, IP addresses are generally not a reliable way to track a session or identify a user.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Many computers designed to be used by a single user, such as office PCs or home PCs, are behind a network address translator (NAT).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This means that several PCs will share a public IP address.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Furthermore, some systems, such as Tor, are designed to retain Internet anonymity, rendering tracking by IP address impractical, impossible, or a security risk.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Because ETags are cached by the browser, and returned with subsequent requests for the same resource, a tracking server can simply repeat any ETag received from the browser to ensure an assigned ETag persists indefinitely (in a similar way to persistent cookies).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Additional caching header fields can also enhance the preservation of ETag data.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] ETags can be flushed in some browsers by clearing the browser cache.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The browser cache can also be used to store information that can be used to track individual users.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] This technique takes advantage of the fact that the web browser will use resources stored within the cache instead of downloading them from the website when it determines that the cache already has the most up-to-date version of the resource.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] For example, a website could serve a JavaScript file with code that sets a unique identifier for the user (for example, `var userId = 3243242;`).
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] After the user's initial visit, every time the user accesses the page, this file will be loaded from the cache instead of downloaded from the server.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] A browser fingerprint is information collected about a browser's configuration, such as version number, screen resolution, and operating system, for the purpose of identification.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Fingerprints can be used to fully or partially identify individual users or devices even when cookies are turned off.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Basic web browser configuration information has long been collected by web analytics services in an effort to accurately measure real human web traffic and discount various forms of click fraud.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] With the assistance of client-side scripting languages, collection of much more esoteric parameters is possible.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Assimilation of such information into a single string constitutes a device fingerprint.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] In 2010, EFF measured at least 18.1 bits of entropy possible from browser fingerprinting.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Canvas fingerprinting, a more recent technique, claims to add another 5.7 bits.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Some web browsers support persistence mechanisms which allow the page to store the information locally for later use.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] The HTML5 standard (which most modern web browsers support to some extent) includes a JavaScript API called Web storage that allows two types of storage: local storage and session storage.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Local storage behaves similarly to persistent cookies while session storage behaves similarly to session cookies, except that session storage is tied to an individual tab/window's lifetime (AKA a page session), not to a whole browser session like session cookies.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Internet Explorer supports persistent information in the browser's history, in the browser's favorites, in an XML store ("user data"), or directly within a web page saved to disk.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] Some web browser plugins include persistence mechanisms as well.
[src:requests-http/http-cookie-p02] For example, Adobe Flash has Local shared object and Microsoft Silverlight has Isolated storage.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:requests-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Although it is known as *URL encoding*, it is also used more generally within the main Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) set, which includes both Uniform Resource Locator (URL) and Uniform Resource Name (URN).
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Consequently, it is also used in the preparation of data of the `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` media type, as is often used in the submission of HTML form data in HTTP requests.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The characters allowed in a URI are either *reserved* or *unreserved* (or a percent character as part of a percent-encoding).
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] *Reserved* characters are those characters that sometimes have special meaning.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] For example, forward slash characters are used to separate different parts of a URL (or, more generally, a URI).
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] *Unreserved* characters have no such meanings.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Using percent-encoding, reserved characters are represented using special character sequences.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The sets of reserved and unreserved characters and the circumstances under which certain reserved characters have special meaning have changed slightly with each revision of specifications that govern URIs and URI schemes.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Other characters in a URI must be percent-encoded.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] When a character from the reserved set (a "reserved character") has a special meaning (a "reserved purpose") in a certain context, and a URI scheme says that it is necessary to use that character for some *other* purpose, then the character must be *percent-encoded*.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Percent-encoding a reserved character involves converting the character to its corresponding byte value in ASCII and then representing that value as a pair of hexadecimal digits (if there is a single hex digit, a leading zero is added).
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The digits, preceded by a percent sign (`%`) as an escape character, are then used in the URI in place of the reserved character.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The reserved character `/`, for example, if used in the "path" component of a URI, has the special meaning of being a delimiter *between* path segments.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] If, according to a given URI scheme, `/` needs to be *in* a path segment, then the three characters `%2F` or `%2f` must be used in the segment instead of a raw `/`.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Reserved characters that have no reserved purpose in a particular context may also be percent-encoded but are not semantically different from those that are not.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] In the "query" component of a URI (the part after a `?` character), for example, `/` is still considered a reserved character but it normally has no reserved purpose, unless a particular URI scheme says otherwise.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The character does not need to be percent-encoded when it has no reserved purpose.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] URIs that differ only by whether a reserved character is percent-encoded or appears literally are normally considered not equivalent (denoting the same resource) unless it can be determined that the reserved characters in question have no reserved purpose.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] This determination is dependent upon the rules established for reserved characters by individual URI schemes.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Characters from the unreserved set never need to be percent-encoded.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] URIs that differ only by whether an unreserved character is percent-encoded or appears literally are equivalent by definition, but URI processors, in practice, may not always recognize this equivalence.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] For example, URI consumers *should not* treat `%41` differently from `A` or `%7E` differently from `~`, but some do.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] For maximal interoperability, URI producers are discouraged from percent-encoding unreserved characters.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Because the percent character ( `%` ) serves to indicate percent-encoded octets, it must itself be percent-encoded as `%25` to be used as data within a URI.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Most URI schemes involve the representation of arbitrary data, such as an IP address or file system path, as components of a URI.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] URI scheme specifications should, but often do not, provide an explicit mapping between URI characters and all possible data values being represented by those characters.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Since the publication of RFC 1738 in 1994 it has been specified that schemes that provide for the representation of binary data in a URI must divide the data into 8-bit bytes and percent-encode each byte in the same manner as above.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Byte value 0x0F, for example, should be represented by `%0F`, but byte value 0x41 can be represented by `A`, or `%41`.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The use of unencoded characters for alphanumeric and other unreserved characters is typically preferred, as it results in shorter URLs.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The procedure for percent-encoding binary data has often been extrapolated, sometimes inappropriately or without being fully specified, to apply to character-based data.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The need to represent characters outside the ASCII range, however, grew quickly, and URI schemes and protocols often failed to provide standard rules for preparing character data for inclusion in a URI.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Web applications consequently began using different multi-byte, stateful, and other non-ASCII-compatible encodings as the basis for percent-encoding, leading to ambiguities and difficulty interpreting URIs reliably.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] For example, many URI schemes and protocols based on RFCs 1738 and 2396 presume that the data characters will be converted to bytes according to some unspecified character encoding before being represented in a URI by unreserved characters or percent-encoded bytes.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] If the scheme does not allow the URI to provide a hint as to what encoding was used, or if the encoding conflicts with the use of ASCII to percent-encode reserved and unreserved characters, then the URI cannot be reliably interpreted.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Some schemes fail to account for encoding at all and instead just suggest that data characters map directly to URI characters, which leaves it up to implementations to decide whether and how to percent-encode data characters that are in neither the reserved nor unreserved sets.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Arbitrary character data is sometimes percent-encoded and used in non-URI situations, such as for password-obfuscation programs or other system-specific translation protocols.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] This suggestion was introduced in January 2005 with the publication of RFC 3986.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] URI schemes introduced before this date are not affected.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Not addressed by the current specification is what to do with encoded character data.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] For example, in computers, character data manifests in encoded form, at some level, and thus could be treated as either binary or character data when being mapped to URI characters.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] Presumably, it is up to the URI scheme specifications to account for this possibility and require one or the other, but in practice, few, if any, actually do.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] There exists a non-standard encoding for Unicode characters: `%u*xxxx*`, where *xxxx* is a UTF-16 code unit represented as four hexadecimal digits.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] For example, the 13th edition of ECMA-262 includes an `escape` function that uses this syntax.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] However, this behavior is not specified by any RFC, and has been rejected by the W3C.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] When data that has been entered into HTML forms is submitted, the form field names and values are encoded and sent to the server in an HTTP request message using method GET or POST, or, historically, via email.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The encoding used by default is based on an early version of the general URI percent-encoding rules, with a number of modifications such as newline normalization and replacing spaces with `+` instead of `%20`.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] The media type of data encoded this way is `application/x-www-form-urlencoded`, and it is currently defined in the HTML and XForms specifications.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] In addition, the CGI specification contains rules for how web servers decode data of this type and make it available to applications.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] When HTML form data is sent in an HTTP GET request, it is included in the query component of the request URI using the same syntax described above.
[src:requests-http/percent-encoding] When sent in an HTTP POST request or via email, the data is placed in the body of the message, and `application/x-www-form-urlencoded` is included in the message's Content-Type header.
[src:requests-http/requests-software] Requests is one of the most downloaded Python libraries, with over 30 million monthly downloads.
[src:requests-http/requests-software] It maps the HTTP protocol onto Python's object-oriented semantics.
[src:requests-http/requests-software] Requests's design has inspired and been copied by HTTP client libraries for other programming languages.
[src:requests-http/requests-software] It is implemented as a wrapper for urllib3, another third-party Python HTTP library.
[src:requests-http/requests-software] Kenneth Reitz, the original author, handed control over to the Python Software Foundation in 2019 after being diagnosed with bipolar disorder in 2015.
[src:requests-http/requests-software] Requests supports TLS/SSL verification, cookies, compression, SOCKS, timeouts, a variety of request methods, and custom headers.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This document covers some of Requests more advanced features.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The Session object allows you to persist certain parameters across requests.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] It also persists cookies across all requests made from the Session instance, and will use `urllib3`’s connection pooling.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] So if you’re making several requests to the same host, the underlying TCP connection will be reused, which can result in a significant performance increase (see HTTP persistent connection).
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] A Session object has all the methods of the main Requests API.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Sessions can also be used to provide default data to the request methods.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Any dictionaries that you pass to a request method will be merged with the session-level values that are set.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The method-level parameters override session parameters.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Note, however, that method-level parameters will *not* be persisted across requests, even if using a session.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you want to manually add cookies to your session, use the Cookie utility functions to manipulate `Session.cookies`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This will make sure the session is closed as soon as the `with` block is exited, even if unhandled exceptions occurred.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Sometimes you’ll want to omit session-level keys from a dict parameter.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] To do this, you simply set that key’s value to `None` in the method-level parameter.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] All values that are contained within a session are directly available to you.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Whenever a call is made to `requests.get()` and friends, you are doing two major things.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] First, you are constructing a `Request` object which will be sent off to a server to request or query some resource.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Second, a `Response` object is generated once Requests gets a response back from the server.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The `Response` object contains all of the information returned by the server and also contains the `Request` object you created originally.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Whenever you receive a `Response` object from an API call or a Session call, the `request` attribute is actually the `PreparedRequest` that was used.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In some cases you may wish to do some extra work to the body or headers (or anything else really) before sending a request.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Since you are not doing anything special with the `Request` object, you prepare it immediately and modify the `PreparedRequest` object.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] You then send that with the other parameters you would have sent to `requests.*` or `Session.*`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] However, the above code will lose some of the advantages of having a Requests `Session` object.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In particular, `Session`-level state such as cookies will not get applied to your request.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] When you are using the prepared request flow, keep in mind that it does not take into account the environment.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This can cause problems if you are using environment variables to change the behaviour of requests.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] For example: Self-signed SSL certificates specified in `REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE` will not be taken into account.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] As a result an `SSL: CERTIFICATE_VERIFY_FAILED` is thrown.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests verifies SSL certificates for HTTPS requests, just like a web browser.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] I don’t have SSL setup on this domain, so it throws an exception.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If `verify` is set to a path to a directory, the directory must have been processed using the `c_rehash` utility supplied with OpenSSL.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This list of trusted CAs can also be specified through the `REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE` environment variable.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If `REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE` is not set, `CURL_CA_BUNDLE` will be used as fallback.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Note that when `verify` is set to `False`, requests will accept any TLS certificate presented by the server, and will ignore hostname mismatches and/or expired certificates, which will make your application vulnerable to man-in-the-middle (MitM) attacks.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Setting verify to `False` may be useful during local development or testing.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Option `verify` only applies to host certs.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The private key to your local certificate *must* be unencrypted.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Currently, Requests does not support using encrypted keys.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests uses certificates from the package certifi.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This allows for users to update their trusted certificates without changing the version of Requests.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Before version 2.16, Requests bundled a set of root CAs that it trusted, sourced from the Mozilla trust store.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The certificates were only updated once for each Requests version.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] When `certifi` was not installed, this led to extremely out-of-date certificate bundles when using significantly older versions of Requests.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] For the sake of security we recommend upgrading certifi frequently!
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] By default, when you make a request, the body of the response is downloaded immediately.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] You can further control the workflow by use of the `Response.iter_content()` and `Response.iter_lines()` methods.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Alternatively, you can read the undecoded body from the underlying urllib3 `urllib3.HTTPResponse` at `Response.raw`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you set `stream` to `True` when making a request, Requests cannot release the connection back to the pool unless you consume all the data or call `Response.close`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This can lead to inefficiency with connections.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Excellent news — thanks to urllib3, keep-alive is 100% automatic within a session!
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Any requests that you make within a session will automatically reuse the appropriate connection!
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Note that connections are only released back to the pool for reuse once all body data has been read; be sure to either set `stream` to `False` or read the `content` property of the `Response` object.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests supports streaming uploads, which allow you to send large streams or files without reading them into memory.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] It is strongly recommended that you open files in binary mode.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This is because Requests may attempt to provide the `Content-Length` header for you, and if it does this value will be set to the number of *bytes* in the file.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Errors may occur if you open the file in *text mode*.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests also supports Chunked transfer encoding for outgoing and incoming requests.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] For chunked encoded responses, it’s best to iterate over the data using `Response.iter_content()`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In an ideal situation you’ll have set `stream=True` on the request, in which case you can iterate chunk-by-chunk by calling `iter_content` with a `chunk_size` parameter of `None`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you want to set a maximum size of the chunk, you can set a `chunk_size` parameter to any integer.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] You can send multiple files in one request.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests has a hook system that you can use to manipulate portions of the request process, or signal event handling.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] That `callback_function` will receive a chunk of data as its first argument.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Your callback function must handle its own exceptions.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Any unhandled exception won’t be passed silently and thus should be handled by the code calling Requests.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If the callback function returns a value, it is assumed that it is to replace the data that was passed in.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If the function doesn’t return anything, nothing else is affected.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] You can add multiple hooks to a single request.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] You can also add hooks to a `Session` instance.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Any hooks you add will then be called on every request made to the session.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] A `Session` can have multiple hooks, which will be called in the order they are added.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests allows you to specify your own authentication mechanism.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Any callable which is passed as the `auth` argument to a request method will have the opportunity to modify the request before it is dispatched.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Authentication implementations are subclasses of `AuthBase`, and are easy to define.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests provides two common authentication scheme implementations in `requests.auth`: `HTTPBasicAuth` and `HTTPDigestAuth`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Let’s pretend that we have a web service that will only respond if the `X-Pizza` header is set to a password value.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] With `Response.iter_lines()` you can easily iterate over streaming APIs such as the Twitter Streaming API.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Calling this method multiple times causes some of the received data being lost.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Setting `session.proxies` may behave differently than expected.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Values provided will be overwritten by environmental proxies (those returned by urllib.request.getproxies).
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] To ensure the use of proxies in the presence of environmental proxies, explicitly specify the `proxies` argument on all individual requests as initially explained above.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] When the proxies configuration is not overridden per request as shown above, Requests relies on the proxy configuration defined by standard environment variables `http_proxy`, `https_proxy`, `no_proxy`, and `all_proxy`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Uppercase variants of these variables are also supported.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Storing sensitive username and password information in an environment variable or a version-controlled file is a security risk and is highly discouraged.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] To give a proxy for a specific scheme and host, use the *scheme://hostname* form for the key.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This will match for any request to the given scheme and exact hostname.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Note that proxy URLs must include the scheme.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Finally, note that using a proxy for https connections typically requires your local machine to trust the proxy’s root certificate.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In addition to basic HTTP proxies, Requests also supports proxies using the SOCKS protocol.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This is an optional feature that requires that additional third-party libraries be installed before use.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Using the scheme `socks5` causes the DNS resolution to happen on the client, rather than on the proxy server.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This is in line with curl, which uses the scheme to decide whether to do the DNS resolution on the client or proxy.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you want to resolve the domains on the proxy server, use `socks5h` as the scheme.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests is intended to be compliant with all relevant specifications and RFCs where that compliance will not cause difficulties for users.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This attention to the specification can lead to some behaviour that may seem unusual to those not familiar with the relevant specification.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] When you receive a response, Requests makes a guess at the encoding to use for decoding the response when you access the `Response.text` attribute.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests will first check for an encoding in the HTTP header, and if none is present, will use charset_normalizer or chardet to attempt to guess the encoding.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If `chardet` is installed, `requests` uses it, however for python3 `chardet` is no longer a mandatory dependency.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The `chardet` library is an LGPL-licenced dependency and some users of requests cannot depend on mandatory LGPL-licensed dependencies.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] When you install `requests` without specifying `[use_chardet_on_py3]` extra, and `chardet` is not already installed, `requests` uses `charset-normalizer` (MIT-licensed) to guess the encoding.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The only time Requests will not guess the encoding is if no explicit charset is present in the HTTP headers **and** the `Content-Type` header contains `text`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In this situation, RFC 2616 specifies that the default charset must be `ISO-8859-1`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests follows the specification in this case.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you require a different encoding, you can manually set the `Response.encoding` property, or use the raw `Response.content`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests provides access to almost the full range of HTTP verbs: GET, OPTIONS, HEAD, POST, PUT, PATCH and DELETE.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The following provides detailed examples of using these various verbs in Requests, using the GitHub API.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] We will begin with the verb most commonly used: GET.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] HTTP GET is an idempotent method that returns a resource from a given URL.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] As a result, it is the verb you ought to use when attempting to retrieve data from a web location.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] An example usage would be attempting to get information about a specific commit from GitHub.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Suppose we wanted commit `a050faf` on Requests.
