[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Time to write a Python program that abuses the GitHub API in all kinds of exciting ways, 4995 more times.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] From time to time you may be working with a server that, for whatever reason, allows use or even requires use of HTTP verbs not covered above.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] One example of this would be the MKCOL method some WEBDAV servers use.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Do not fret, these can still be used with Requests.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] These make use of the built-in `.request` method.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Utilising this, you can make use of any method verb that your server allows.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] They make APIs more self describing and discoverable.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] As of v1.0.0, Requests has moved to a modular internal design using Transport Adapters.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] These objects provide a mechanism to define interaction methods for an HTTP service.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In particular, they allow you to apply per-service configuration.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests ships with a single Transport Adapter, the `HTTPAdapter`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This adapter provides the default Requests interaction with HTTP and HTTPS using the powerful urllib3 library.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Whenever a Requests `Session` is initialized, one of these is attached to the `Session` object for HTTP, and one for HTTPS.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Requests enables users to create and use their own Transport Adapters that provide specific functionality.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Once created, a Transport Adapter can be mounted to a Session object, along with an indication of which web services it should apply to.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The mount call registers a specific instance of a Transport Adapter to a prefix.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Once mounted, any HTTP request made using that session whose URL starts with the given prefix will use the given Transport Adapter.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The adapter will be chosen based on a longest prefix match.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Be mindful prefixes such as `http://localhost` will also match `http://localhost.other.com` or `http://localhost@other.com`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] It’s recommended to terminate full hostnames with a `/`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Many of the details of implementing a Transport Adapter are beyond the scope of this documentation, but take a look at the next example for a simple SSL use- case.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] For more than that, you might look at subclassing the `BaseAdapter`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The Requests team has made a specific choice to use whatever SSL version is default in the underlying library (urllib3).
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Normally this is fine, but from time to time, you might find yourself needing to connect to a service-endpoint that uses a version that isn’t compatible with the default.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] You can use Transport Adapters for this by taking most of the existing implementation of HTTPAdapter, and adding a parameter *ssl_version* that gets passed-through to *urllib3*.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] By default, Requests does not retry failed connections.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] With the default Transport Adapter in place, Requests does not provide any kind of non-blocking IO.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The `Response.content` property will block until the entire response has been downloaded.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you require more granularity, the streaming features of the library (see Streaming Requests) allow you to retrieve smaller quantities of the response at a time.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you are concerned about the use of blocking IO, there are lots of projects out there that combine Requests with one of Python’s asynchronicity frameworks.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Some excellent examples are requests-threads, grequests, requests-futures, and httpx.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In unusual circumstances you may want to provide headers in an ordered manner.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If you pass an `OrderedDict` to the `headers` keyword argument, that will provide the headers with an ordering.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] *However*, the ordering of the default headers used by Requests will be preferred, which means that if you override default headers in the `headers` keyword argument, they may appear out of order compared to other headers in that keyword argument.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If this is problematic, users should consider setting the default headers on a `Session` object, by setting `Session.headers` to a custom `OrderedDict`.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Most requests to external servers should have a timeout attached, in case the server is not responding in a timely manner.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] By default, requests do not time out unless a timeout value is set explicitly.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Without a timeout, your code may hang for minutes or more.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The **connect** timeout is the number of seconds Requests will wait for your client to establish a connection to a remote machine (corresponding to the connect()) call on the socket.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] It’s a good practice to set connect timeouts to slightly larger than a multiple of 3, which is the default TCP packet retransmission window.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Once your client has connected to the server and sent the HTTP request, the **read** timeout is the number of seconds the client will wait for the server to send a response.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] (Specifically, it’s the number of seconds that the client will wait *between* bytes sent from the server.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] In 99.9% of cases, this is the time before the server sends the first byte).
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The timeout value will be applied to both the `connect` and the `read` timeouts.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If the remote server is very slow, you can tell Requests to wait forever for a response, by passing None as a timeout value and then retrieving a cup of coffee.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] The connect timeout applies to each connection attempt to an IP address.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] If multiple addresses exist for a domain name, the underlying `urllib3` will try each address sequentially until one successfully connects.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This may lead to an effective total connection timeout *multiple* times longer than the specified time, e.g. an unresponsive server having both IPv4 and IPv6 addresses will have its perceived timeout *doubled*, so take that into account when setting the connection timeout.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] Neither the connect nor read timeouts are wall clock.
[src:requests-http/user-advanced] This means that if you start a request, and look at the time, and then look at the time when the request finishes or times out, the real-world time may be greater than what you specified.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] This page gives a good introduction in how to get started with Requests.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Let’s get started with some simple examples.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Making a request with Requests is very simple.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Now, we have a `Response` object called `r`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] We can get all the information we need from this object.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Requests’ simple API means that all forms of HTTP request are as obvious.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] What about the other HTTP request types: PUT, DELETE, HEAD and OPTIONS?
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] That’s all well and good, but it’s also only the start of what Requests can do.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] You often want to send some sort of data in the URL’s query string.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If you were constructing the URL by hand, this data would be given as key/value pairs in the URL after a question mark, e.g.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Requests allows you to provide these arguments as a dictionary of strings, using the `params` keyword argument.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Note that any dictionary key whose value is `None` will not be added to the URL’s query string.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] We can read the content of the server’s response.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Requests will automatically decode content from the server.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Most unicode charsets are seamlessly decoded.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] When you make a request, Requests makes educated guesses about the encoding of the response based on the HTTP headers.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The text encoding guessed by Requests is used when you access `r.text`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If you change the encoding, Requests will use the new value of `r.encoding` whenever you call `r.text`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] You might want to do this in any situation where you can apply special logic to work out what the encoding of the content will be.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] For example, HTML and XML have the ability to specify their encoding in their body.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] In situations like this, you should use `r.content` to find the encoding, and then set `r.encoding`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] This will let you use `r.text` with the correct encoding.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Requests will also use custom encodings in the event that you need them.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If you have created your own encoding and registered it with the `codecs` module, you can simply use the codec name as the value of `r.encoding` and Requests will handle the decoding for you.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The `gzip` and `deflate` transfer-encodings are automatically decoded for you.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The `br` transfer-encoding is automatically decoded for you if a Brotli library like brotli or brotlicffi is installed.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] In case the JSON decoding fails, `r.json()` raises an exception.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] For example, if the response gets a 204 (No Content), or if the response contains invalid JSON, attempting `r.json()` raises `requests.exceptions.JSONDecodeError`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] This wrapper exception provides interoperability for multiple exceptions that may be thrown by different python versions and json serialization libraries.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] It should be noted that the success of the call to `r.json()` does **not** indicate the success of the response.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Some servers may return a JSON object in a failed response (e.g. error details with HTTP 500).
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] To check that a request is successful, use `r.raise_for_status()` or check `r.status_code` is what you expect.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] In the rare case that you’d like to get the raw socket response from the server, you can access `r.raw`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If you want to do this, make sure you set `stream=True` in your initial request.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Using `Response.iter_content` will handle a lot of what you would otherwise have to handle when using `Response.raw` directly.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] When streaming a download, the above is the preferred and recommended way to retrieve the content.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Note that `chunk_size` can be freely adjusted to a number that may better fit your use cases.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] An important note about using `Response.iter_content` versus `Response.raw`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] `Response.iter_content` will automatically decode the `gzip` and `deflate` transfer-encodings.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] `Response.raw` is a raw stream of bytes – it does not transform the response content.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If you really need access to the bytes as they were returned, use `Response.raw`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If you’d like to add HTTP headers to a request, simply pass in a `dict` to the `headers` parameter.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Note: Custom headers are given less precedence than more specific sources of information.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Furthermore, Requests does not change its behavior at all based on which custom headers are specified.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The headers are simply passed on into the final request.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Note: All header values must be a `string`, bytestring, or unicode.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] While permitted, it’s advised to avoid passing unicode header values.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Typically, you want to send some form-encoded data — much like an HTML form.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] To do this, simply pass a dictionary to the `data` argument.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The `data` argument can also have multiple values for each key.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] This can be done by making `data` either a list of tuples or a dictionary with lists as values.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] There are times that you may want to send data that is not form-encoded.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If you pass in a `string` instead of a `dict`, that data will be posted directly.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Please note that the above code will NOT add the `Content-Type` header (so in particular it will NOT set it to `application/json`).
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Note, the `json` parameter is ignored if either `data` or `files` is passed.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] In the event you are posting a very large file as a `multipart/form-data` request, you may want to stream the request.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] By default, `requests` does not support this, but there is a separate package which does - `requests-toolbelt`.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] You should read the toolbelt’s documentation for more details about how to use it.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] For sending multiple files in one request refer to the advanced section.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The dictionary is special, though: it’s made just for HTTP headers.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] According to RFC 7230, HTTP Header names are case-insensitive.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Cookies are returned in a `RequestsCookieJar`, which acts like a `dict` but also offers a more complete interface, suitable for use over multiple domains or paths.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] By default Requests will perform location redirection for all verbs except HEAD.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] We can use the `history` property of the Response object to track redirection.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The `Response.history` list contains the `Response` objects that were created in order to complete the request.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] The list is sorted from the oldest to the most recent response.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] You can tell Requests to stop waiting for a response after a given number of seconds with the `timeout` parameter.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] Nearly all production code should use this parameter in nearly all requests.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] `timeout` is not a time limit on the entire response download; rather, an exception is raised if the server has not issued a response for `timeout` seconds (more precisely, if no bytes have been received on the underlying socket for `timeout` seconds).
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If no timeout is specified explicitly, requests do not time out.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] DNS failure, refused connection, etc), Requests will raise a `ConnectionError` exception.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] `Response.raise_for_status()` will raise an `HTTPError` if the HTTP request returned an unsuccessful status code.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If a request times out, a `Timeout` exception is raised.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] If a request exceeds the configured number of maximum redirections, a `TooManyRedirects` exception is raised.
[src:requests-http/user-quickstart] All exceptions that Requests explicitly raises inherit from `requests.exceptions.RequestException`.
